{"title_page": "Girl next door", "text_new": "{{About|the stock character|other uses|Girl Next Door (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n[[File:Dik_Trom_en_the_blind_girl_next_door_by_Johan_Braakensiek_end_of_19th_century.png|thumb|[[Dik Trom]] and the blind girl next door (by [[Johan Braakensiek]])]]\n\nThe '''girl next door''' is a [[Girl|young female]] [[stock character]] who is often used in [[Romance novel|romantic stories]]. She is so named because she often lives next door to the protagonist or is a childhood friend. They start out with a mutual [[friendship]] that later often develops into romantic attraction.\n\nA similar expression is \"[[wikt:boy next door|boy next door]]\".\n\n== Characteristics ==\nA \"girl next door\" character is often seen as natural, unpretentious, and a [[tomboy]]. A trope that evokes [[nostalgia]], it is associated with small towns and more local or even rural ways of life.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Doris Day Confidential: Hollywood, Sex and Stardom|last=McDonald|first=Tamar Jeffers|publisher=|isbn=978-0857722799|location=London|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=8d74AAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22girl+next+door%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiTy4CU3rzkAhUuHjQIHWe9C0MQ6AEwCHoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=%22Doris%20Day%22%20%22girl%20next%20door%22&f=false 77-86]|oclc=862101452|date = 2013-09-27}}</ref> The girl next door is often portrayed as an innocent [[Virginity|virgin]] who lacks the [[promiscuity]] or sexual sophistication that is associated with the big city.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[Doris Day]] of 1950s is described as a pioneering embodiment of the \"girl next door\" image in film,<ref name=\":0\"/> the \"Hollywood's girl next door\".<ref>[https://www.wprl.org/post/actress-and-singer-doris-day-hollywoods-girl-next-door-dies-97 \"Actress And Singer Doris Day, Hollywood's Girl Next Door, Dies At 97\"]</ref>\n\nA common cliche is when a male protagonist is caught in a [[love triangle]] between two women, he will usually choose the \"sweet, ordinary, and caring girl next door\" he grew up with rather than a more well-off or beautiful woman with fewer morals.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Ebert's bigger little movie glossary : a greatly expanded and much improved compendium of movie clich\u00e9s, stereotypes, obligatory scenes, hackneyed formulas, shopworn conventions, and outdated archetypes|date=1999|publisher=Andrews McMeel|others=Ebert, Roger.|isbn=0740792466|location=Kansas City, Mo.|oclc=829154479}}</ref> Other times, this character ignores the hero for another male character, despite being the object of his affections.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Romancing the zombie : essays on the undead as significant \"other\"|publisher=|others=Szanter, Ashley,, Richards, Jessica K.,, Bishop, Kyle William, 1973-|isbn=978-1476667423|location=Jefferson, North Carolina|pages=45|oclc=987796701|date = 2017-08-14}}</ref>{{better source|date=July 2018}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Farmer's daughter]]\n*[[Friend zone]]\n* [[Innamorati]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last1=Levine |first1=Michal P. |last2=Schneider |first2=Steven Jay |editor-last=South |editor-first=James B. |title=Buffy the Vampire Slayer and Philosophy: Fear and Trembling in Sunnydale |chapter=Feeling for Buffy: The Girl Next Door |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=dx_n2IDCJqUC&pg=PA294&lpg=PA294&focus=viewport&vq=%22Feeling+for+Buffy:+The+Girl+Next+Door.%22&dq=Buffy+the+Vampire+Slayer+and+Philosophy:+Fear+and+Trembling+in+Sunnydale#v=onepage&q=%22Feeling%20for%20Buffy%3A%20The%20Girl%20Next%20Door.%22&f=false |year=2003 |publisher=Open Court |isbn=978-0-8126-9531-1 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/buffyvampireslay00sout/page/294 294\u2013308] |title-link=Buffy the Vampire Slayer and Philosophy: Fear and Trembling in Sunnydale }}  \n**From a review: \"To Michal Levine and Steven Jay Schneider ... Buffy is just another unconscious Freudian reality tale starring the proverbial girl next door.\" - in: ''[[Joss Whedon]]: The Complete Companion: The TV Series, the Movies, the Comic Books, and More''\n* {{cite news|last1=Frank Rich|first1=Rich|title=Journal: The Girl Next Door|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/02/20/opinion/journal-the-girl-next-door.html|accessdate=January 30, 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=February 20, 1994|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503063929/http://www.nytimes.com/1994/02/20/opinion/journal-the-girl-next-door.html|archivedate=2009-05-03|url-status=live|author1-link=Frank Rich}}\n**The article criticizes ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' for their misuse of term \"girl next door\": \"Otherwise the magazine is still pushing what Ms. Brinkley repeatedly described as the \"natural beauty\" of \"what readers long for -- the girl next door\". Who is the girl next door? Her fake name keeps changing but she is still the same empty-headed, smiling, air-brushed mannequin who appeared in Playboy in the 1950s and early 60s...\"\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|girl next door}}\n\n{{Stock characters}}\n\n[[Category:Stereotypes of women]]\n[[Category:Female stock characters]]\n\n\n{{lit-char-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the stock character|other uses|Girl Next Door (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n[[File:Dik_Trom_en_the_blind_girl_next_door_by_Johan_Braakensiek_end_of_19th_century.png|thumb|[[Dik Trom]] and the blind girl next door (by [[Johan Braakensiek]])]]\n\nThe '''girl next door''' is a [[Girl|young female]] [[stock character]] who is often used in [[Romance novel|romantic stories]]. She is so named because she often lives next door to the protagonist or is a childhood friend. They start out with a mutual [[friendship]] that later often develops into romantic attraction.\n\nA similar expression is \"[[wikt:boy next door|boy next door]]\".\n\n== Characteristics ==\nA \"girl next door\" character is often seen as natural, unpretentious, and a [[tomboy]]. A trope that evokes [[nostalgia]], it is associated with small towns and more local or even rural ways of life.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Doris Day Confidential: Hollywood, Sex and Stardom|last=McDonald|first=Tamar Jeffers|publisher=|isbn=978-0857722799|location=London|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=8d74AAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22girl+next+door%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiTy4CU3rzkAhUuHjQIHWe9C0MQ6AEwCHoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=%22Doris%20Day%22%20%22girl%20next%20door%22&f=false 77-86]|oclc=862101452|date = 2013-09-27}}</ref> The girl next door is often portrayed as an innocent [[Virginity|virgin]] who lacks the [[promiscuity]] or sexual sophistication that is associated with the big city.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[Doris Day]] of 1950s is described as a pioneering embodiment of the \"girl next door\" image in film,<ref name=\":0\"/> the \"Hollywood's girl next door\".<ref>[https://www.wprl.org/post/actress-and-singer-doris-day-hollywoods-girl-next-door-dies-97 \"Actress And Singer Doris Day, Hollywood's Girl Next Door, Dies At 97\"]</ref>\n\nA common cliche is when a male protagonist is caught in a [[love triangle]] between two women, he will usually choose the \"sweet, ordinary, and caring girl next door\" he grew up with rather than a more well-off or beautiful woman with fewer morals.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Ebert's bigger little movie glossary : a greatly expanded and much improved compendium of movie clich\u00e9s, stereotypes, obligatory scenes, hackneyed formulas, shopworn conventions, and outdated archetypes|date=1999|publisher=Andrews McMeel|others=Ebert, Roger.|isbn=0740792466|location=Kansas City, Mo.|oclc=829154479}}</ref> Other times, this character ignores the hero for another male character, despite being the object of his affections.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Romancing the zombie : essays on the undead as significant \"other\"|publisher=|others=Szanter, Ashley,, Richards, Jessica K.,, Bishop, Kyle William, 1973-|isbn=978-1476667423|location=Jefferson, North Carolina|pages=45|oclc=987796701|date = 2017-0